In Week 15, the pattern that had been forming since the start of the term came into sharp relief. Power moved further toward a presidency that governs by decree, backed by a justice system bent to its will, a civil service stripped of neutrality, and an information sphere reshaped to favor the regime\'92s story. The week\'92s events did not just add more orders and more controversies; they showed how many levers of the state could be pulled at once to reward allies, punish critics, and redraw the boundaries of belonging. It was a week in which citizenship, law, and truth themselves were sorted into hierarchies, and in which the tools meant to guard against abuse were turned into instruments of it.\
\
At the start of this period, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:38 p.m. By the end of Week 15, it read 7:43 p.m., a movement of just over four minutes deeper into the danger zone. That shift reflects not a single spectacular break, but a dense cluster of structural changes: emergency powers used as routine policy tools, the Department of Justice recast as shield and sword for the president, the civil service reclassified for loyalty, and independent media and universities brought under direct pressure. Courts, some state officials, and mass protests did push back in places, but their gains were defensive and narrow. The net effect was to make the new order harder to unwind.\
\
The most visible strand of the week was the further normalization of rule by emergency and executive order. Trump\'92s earlier declaration of a national emergency at the southern border, used to deploy troops and hardline policies, was now joined by a national \'93energy emergency\'94 to open more land and ocean to drilling, and by a sweeping use of the International Emergency Economic Powers Act to impose a 145% tariff on Chinese goods. These moves bypassed Congress and treated extraordinary powers as a standing toolkit for trade, immigration, and energy. When congressional Democrats tried to claw back tariff authority, Republicans in both chambers used procedure to block votes, leaving the emergency structure intact. The presidency grew more unilateral, and the legislature more performative. That was the point.\
\
