The same logic appeared in the way federal power was turned against disfavored states and institutions. Sanctuary cities and states that resisted federal immigration demands were targeted by an order to list and punish them, with threats to cut off funds. Maine saw its child nutrition funds frozen when it refused to bar transgender girls from girls\'92 sports, and only a negotiated settlement restored the money. Michigan and Hawaii were sued by the Department of Justice to stop their climate lawsuits against oil companies, and Puerto Rico dropped its own climate case under pressure. Universities that resisted federal dictates on speech and diversity, such as Harvard and Chicago\'92s public schools, were threatened with the loss of billions in funding or subjected to civil-rights investigations. Federal power, once meant to equalize protection, was now used to discipline. It was a clear warning to any jurisdiction that stepped out of line.\
