The Department of Justice sat at the center of this transformation. Under Attorney General Pam Bondi, DOJ created a \'93weaponization working group\'94 whose very purpose was to frame investigations into Trump\'92s past conduct as partisan attacks. It closed its cryptocurrency enforcement unit after complaints from industry allies, paused prosecutions under the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act for six months, and dropped investigations and lawsuits against 89 corporations, many of them donors. At the same time, it opened a politically charged investigation into ActBlue, the Democrats\'92 main online fundraising platform, on unproven allegations of foreign money, and pursued law firms that had successfully sued Fox News over election lies. The message was plain: enforcement would fall on opponents and inconvenient industries, while friends would see their liabilities erased. Law was no longer a neutral limit; it was a tool of selection.\
