The president\'92s pardon power was folded into this pattern. In addition to the earlier mass pardons for January 6 defendants, which directed DOJ to dismiss remaining cases and signaled tolerance for political violence in service of the regime, new pardons wiped out more than a billion dollars in restitution owed by white\uc0\u8209 collar offenders. Figures convicted of fraud and embezzlement saw their debts to victims vanish; a cryptocurrency exchange had a $100 million fine erased. These acts did not just free individuals; they rewrote the financial consequences of elite crime. Combined with the halt in FCPA prosecutions and the closure of the crypto unit, they told a donor class that legal risk could be managed politically. Accountability became negotiable for those with the right ties.\
