The economic consequences of this model were already visible. Sweeping tariffs on imports from China, Mexico, Canada, and beyond, combined with \'93reciprocal tariffs\'94 of up to 49% on all goods, drove capital flight and raised borrowing costs for the U.S. government. Factory orders and shipments fell; manufacturers delayed investment; ports projected a 35% drop in shipping volumes. UPS announced layoffs of 20,000 workers and the closure of 73 facilities, citing tariff\uc0\u8209 driven declines in volume. Tesla raised prices in Canada, depressing demand. Tourism from overseas dropped sharply as deportations and trade wars made the United States seem hostile and expensive. The Bureau of Economic Analysis reported a 0.3% contraction in GDP in the first quarter of 2025, the first in three years. Yet the White House insisted that tariffs were not to blame, and Trump publicly claimed any downturn was Biden\'92s fault. Economic data became another field to be spun.\
